<TITLE> Nation pays tribute to Ekushey martyrs</font> </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 20 (bdnews24.com)  President Iajuddin Ahmed was the first to lay a wreath at the Central Shaheed Minar a minute past Wednesday midnight, commemorating the sacrifices of Language Movement martyrs. . Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed followed suit. Next came the members of the cabinet. Speaker Jamiruddin Sircar and deputy speaker Akhter Hamid Siddiqui placed a wreath together, followed by Dhaka mayor Sadek Hossain Khoka and delegates of the Diplomatic Corps in Bangladesh. Dhaka University vice-chancellor SMA Faiz also placed a wreath. The president and the chief adviser paid tribute in separate messages on the occasion, calling for broader unity among people. "February 21, 1952, is a historic and significant day in our national life. I pay deep tribute to the Ekushey martyrs and pray for the salvation of the souls of those who sacrificed their lives in the Language Movement," Iajuddin said. Fakhruddin, in his message, urged all to build national unity by rising above partisan attitudes and differences of opinion. "On the occasion of glorious Shaheed Day and International Mother Language Day, I extend good wishes to all Bangla-speaking people throughout the world including my countrymen," said the chief adviser. Acting Awami League president Zillur Rahman in a message on the eve of Amar Ekushey said: "In 1952, the martyrs established the mother language by sacrificing their lives." "As a result of their sacrifices, 188 countries now commemorate February 21 as International Mother Language Day. The glory belongs to the language, literature and culture of the Bangalis." Zillur said that Ekushey meant a struggle, and that the lovers of Bangla language and culture should build a united movement against all forms of repression. The Awami League has chalked out programmes marking Amar Ekushey that include laying wreaths at the Central Shaheed Minar, holding a morning procession and laying flowers at the graves of the language movement martyrsat Azimpur graveyard. The party will hoist the national and party flags at half mast and also hoist black flags at its central office and all unit offices across the country. BNP acting office secretary Rizvi Ahmed said that the party would organise a discussion on the Shaheed Dibash at the Engineers Institute auditorium at 3 pm Thursday. Workers Party president, Rashed Khan Menon, and general secretary Bimal Biswas, expressed deep respect for the memory of the language martyrs. The party will offer wreaths at the Central Shaheed Minar at 12 minutes past midnight. Bikalpadhara president AQM Badruddoza Chowdhury said the nation had yet to show real honour to the sacrifice of the language heroes and the Bangla language Bangladesher Samajtantrik Dal, Democratic Left Front, Samajtantrik Mohila Forum, Samajtantrik Chhatra Front, Charon Sangskritik Kendro, Bangladesh Chhatra League and Bangladesh Jatiyatabadi Chhatra Dal have also chalked out different programmes on the occasion. The Rapid Action Battalion has put in place a "foolproof' security arrangement for the Central Shaheed Minar and environs for the day. The elite security force will use helicoptersif necessaryto strengthen security measures, RAB-3 chief Sultan Mohammad Noorani said at a news briefing Tuesday. Some 600 RAB members have been deployed at the Central Shaheed Minar along with other security forces. Two hundred RAB officers are in plainclothes. Checkpoints are put up on Fuller Road, TSC, Doyel Crossing, Plassey, Chankharpul and BDR Gate. Observation towers have been set up in the Shaheed Minar area to ensure security for people. bdness24.com/sm
